title: For Sale:  German Gew 88 Commission Rifle
location: North of Dayton, St Marys, Dayton, Ohio
postcontent:
This antique rifle is non-functional. See missing parts below. The Gew 88 (commonly called the Model 1888 commission rifle) was a late 19th-century German bolt action rifle, adopted in 1888. It was developed by the Arms Commission in Spandau Germany. The Gew. 88 was originally manufactured for the 7,9x57 cartridge, loaded with nitro-powder. In 1902, Germany adopted the S-patrone (with lighter and much faster “Spitzer” or pointed bullet) many of the Gew.88 rifles were adapted for this new ammunition. These rifles (rechambered and re-grooved), are often referred to as “Gew.88S”, and are clearly marked with the letter “S” stamped on the top of receiver, in front of the ejection opening. A special feature of the G.88 rifle is the tubular barrel jacket, which is screwed onto the front of the receiver. This jacket is intended to protect the barrel from rough handling and elements. The overall condition is fair to good. The bore is bright and the rifling is solid. Made in 1891 at the Imperial Arsenal at Loewe Berlin. Serial Number 5356 matches: The barrel, receiver, stock. The bolt serial number does not match. The barrel cover has another serial number on it, likely swapped out when it was rechambered. There is a Prussian “crown” above an “S” cartouche on the buttstock. The receiver has the unit marking 164.R.5.64.   This rifle is all original and with factory modifications. It is missing the bolt head with extractor and ejector, rear sight, the cleaning rod and the magazine dust cover. The weapon is non-functional without the bolthead, extractor and ejector.
Here are the Specs: Gew.88 rifle. Caliber/ cartridge: 7.92x57 S-patrone. Overall length: 1240 mm / 48.8”. Barrel length: 740 mm / 29.1”. Weight, empty: 3.8 kg / 8.37 lbs. Magazine capacity: 5 rounds.
Local pickup, Cash preferred. $180 or best reasonable offer received. Contact me for additional pictures or to make an offer.

postcontent: PRODUCT DESCRIPTION The Flat Dark Earth version of the P-10 C with night sights Many years in the making, we’re pleased to announce the latest addition to the CZ line of handguns — the P-10 C. Much more than just our take on the striker-fired pistol, the P-10 is decidedly CZ, from the way it feels to the way it shoots. First order of business, ergonomics. Anyone who’s picked up a CZ 75 for the first time gets it — it just has to feel right in the hand. With the CZ grip angle, the P-10 avoids that ‘brick-in-the-hand’ feeling that has plagued many in the striker-fired genre, allowing it to point naturally. A mild palm swell, deep beavertail and three interchangeable backstraps make the P-10 fit a wide variety of hands as if it were built for them. Because it was. Next up, trigger. So many striker-fired pistols do many things right, falling short when it comes time to pull the trigger. The P-10’s trigger is designed to minimize creep and stacking, and after initial break-in averages a clean 4.5-5 lb pull and rebounds with a short, positive reset — meaning single shots can be meticulously placed while follow-ups are effortless. Built to withstand the rigors of military use, its fiber-reinforced polymer frame and hardy nitride finish are made for the daily grind. A generous trigger guard allows use with gloved hands while being undercut to allow as high a grip as possible, and a set of metal tactical sights allow for one-handed manipulation of the slide on a belt. Like all CZ pistols, the P-10 is built with our legendary cold hammer forged barrel. The ‘C’ in the name indicates that it is compact in both frame and slide size, and magazines are of the same family as the hammer-fired P-07, meaning the P-10 C holds 15+1 in 9mm in a flush-fitting mag with extended bases allowing 17+1. Take-down of the P-10 will be familiar to most fans of striker-fired guns, and even more pleasing will be holster compatibility with some of the most common guns on the market. It may have taken a while to come to market, but we feel the wait has been worth it. title: For Sale/Trade:  Make Offer: M1 Garand
postcontent: I have for sale or trade my M1 Garand.  It is an HRA Korean War Era Garand.   It was rebuilt in 1963 by Springfield which can be told by its barrel date and the second P Proof mark on the stock.  The receiver is HRA and the rest from what I can tell is Springfield.  Both arsenals are desireable making this the best of both worlds in terms of quality.  The metal finish is very nice and the stock is of very good surplus quality with handling marks.  It still retains the rack number, a slight DoD inspection mark, and of course the two P's from arsenal.  The fact it was re-arsenaled in 1963 lends itself to explain that it could have been used as a training rifle during the Vietnam Era.  It also still retains an uncut op-rod which is quite rare.  The barrel is in very good condition.Make me an offer for sale or trade.  If you would like any more info or pictures just ask.  Please do not contact me and explain that "you can get Garands for $700."  If you can get them that cheaply, I urge you to do so and go ahead and let me know so I can get in on that.  *Must be willing to sign Bill of Sale* I am located in Clarksville, I am willing to travel as far as about an hour away in TN assuming the trade is good enough..
